After Japan annexed the Ryukyu Kingdom in 1879, the Meiji government began attempts at absorbing the Ryukyuan religion into [[:en:State Shinto|State Shinto]]. The priestesses and their shrines were co-opted by the government and registered. The {{transliteration|ja|noro}} were prohibited from being recognized as part of the Shinto priesthood and, unlike their Shinto counterparts, were not guaranteed protection by the state. Furthermore, the government abolished their salaries. While the government was unable to confiscate {{transliteration|ja|noro}} land, in 1910 their land were commuted to monetary stipends which were then limited in use to exclude personal expense, leaving the {{transliteration|ja|noro}} with no government income. Then-Governor of Okinawa Prefecture [[:en:Hibi Shigeaki|Hibi Shigeaki]] stated that this limitation on the use of {{transliteration|ja|noro}} land stipends was "for the maintenance of {{transliteration|ja|noro}} lands [...] for their eventual reclassification into [Shinto] shrines."<ref>Tze May Loo, ''Heritage Politics: Shuri Castle and Okinawa's Incorporation into Modern Japan'' (New York: Lexington Books, 2014), 102.</ref> As the influence of {{transliteration|ja|noro}} declined, the popularity of {{transliteration|ja|yuta}} increased.
The chaos of the [[:en:Battle of Okinawa|Battle of Okinawa]] severely reduced and scattered Okinawa's population, which further minimized the function of the {{transliteration|ja|noro}}. {{transliteration|ja|Noro}} today only exist in rural villages and at {{transliteration|ja|[[utaki]]}} sites.{{cn|date=June 2022}}
=={{transliteration|ja|Kikoe-ōgimi}}== {{main|Kikoe-ōgimi}}
The {{nihongo||聞得大君|kikoe-ōgimi}} (Okinawan: {{transliteration|ja|chifi-ufujin}}) served as the priestess for the Ryukyu Kingdom and the royal family. She conducted national ceremonies, oversaw all other {{transliteration|ja|noro}} priestesses, and maintained the royal hearth and the most sacred {{transliteration|ja|utaki}}.<ref>George H. Kerr, ''Okinawa: History of an Island People'' (Tokyo: Charles E. Tuttle Company, 1958), 110-111.</ref> The inauguration ceremony, {{nihongo||御新下り|uarauri}}, of a new {{transliteration|ja|kikoe-ōgimi}} was held at Seifa-utaki. The ceremony represented the holy marriage between Amamikyu and Shinerikyu. Religiously, the holy marriage gave the {{transliteration|ja|kikoe-ōgimi}} spiritual power supported by {{nihongo||君手摩|[[kimitezuri]]}}. After she was inaugurated, she stayed in the position until her death. The position was abolished along with the kingdom in 1879; however, the last {{transliteration|ja|kikoe-ōgimi}} continued her role until her death in 1944.
=={{transliteration|ja|Noro}} duties and responsibilities==
{{transliteration|ja|Noro}} were responsible for maintaining the village hearth and helping to establish new households.<ref>George H. Kerr, ''Okinawa: History of an Island People'' (Tokyo: Charles E. Tuttle Company, 1958), 32.</ref> They primarily conducted rituals and ceremonies for their respective village at a local {{transliteration|ja|utaki}}. Girls from each family in a village were assigned to be the {{transliteration|ja|noro}}'s assistant, although men could also be assistants for public ceremonies.<ref>Susan Sered, ''Women of the Sacred Grove: Divine Priestesses of Okinawa'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 1999), 3-4, 18.</ref> {{transliteration|ja|Noro}} also communicated with and channeled ancestors and deities.
==Symbols==
{{transliteration|ja|Noro}} are most recognizable by their white robes and headdress, which symbolize spiritual purity.<ref>George H. Kerr, ''Okinawa: History of an Island People'' (Tokyo: Charles E. Tuttle Company, 1958), 33.</ref> They also wear or carry beads and a {{transliteration|ja|[[magatama]]}} stone. The {{transliteration|ja|noro}}'s hearth includes three stones teepee-ed together; the stones always come from the shore.<ref>George H. Kerr, ''Okinawa: History of an Island People'' (Tokyo: Charles E. Tuttle Company, 1958), 32-33.</ref>
==Hierarchy==
{| class="wikitable" |+ Priestess hierarchy ! Title ! Description |- ! {{nihongo||聞得大君|[[:en:Kikoe-ōgimi|Kikoe-ōgimi]]||extra=Okinawan: {{transliteration|ryu|chifi ufujin}}}} | Royal priestess, a blood relative of the king, residing in Shuri. |- ! {{transliteration|ja|Izena noro}} | Directly ruled [[:en:Izena, Okinawa|Izena]] Magiri. |- ! {{transliteration|ja|Kudaka noro}} | Directly ruled [[:en:Kudaka Island|Kudaka Island]]. |- ! {{transliteration|ja|[[Mihara-oamu-shirare]]}} | Priestesses in charge of the three [[:en:Administrative divisions of the Ryukyu Kingdom|districts]] of Kunigami, Nakagami, and Shimajiri. |- ! {{transliteration|ja|Noro}} | Village or {{transliteration|ja|[[:en:Magiri|Magiri]]}} priestess. |- ! Assistants | Typically a girl representing a family in a village or a {{transliteration|ja|noro}}-in-training, but can be a man for public ceremonies. |}
